Mrs. Linton bent forward, and listened
breathlessly. The minute after a step tra-
versed the hall; the open house was too
tempting for Heathcliff to resist walking in:
most likely he supposed that I was inclined to
sbirk my promise, and so resolved to trust to his
own audacity.

VVith straining eagerness Catherine gazed
towards the entrance of her chamber. He did
not hit the right room directly; she motioned
me to admit him; but he found it out, ere I
could reach the door, and in a stride or two
was at her side, and had her grasped in his
arms.

He neither spoke, nor loosed his hold, for
some ﬁve minutes, during which period he be-

stowed more kisses than ever he gave in his

